description:
Some Coast Tarweed (Madia sativa), photographed at Wavecrest Open Space in Half Moon Bay, CA.  This is a fairly tall species for the genus Madia, with not very showy flowers and lots of sticky, glandular hairs that have a strong, tar-like scent. Its croweded, spike-like inflorescence, relatively large flowers (with involucres generally greater than 10mm in diameter), and its lanceolate leaves distingusih it from the other tarweeds lacking showy flowers in the genus Madia that can be found in the San Francisco Bay Area (i.e., M. exigua, M. anomala, and M. gracilis).

Note:  This specis is also known as the Chile Tarweed, Chilean Tarweed, or Coast Madia.

References:
1)  Bruce G. Baldwin 2012, Madia sativa, in Jepson Flora Project (eds.) Jepson eFlora, /eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=4055, accessed on August 07, 2020
2) Bruce G. Baldwin 2012, Madia, in Jepson Flora Project (eds.) Jepson eFlora, /eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=517, accessed on August 07, 2020.
3) Key to Madia (n.d.).  Jepson eFlora.  Retrieved on 8/7/20 from https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_keys.php?key=517
4) Madia sativa Molina (n.d.).  Calflora database.  Retrieved on 8/7/20 from https://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-calrecnum=5298
5) Madia sativa (n.d.). Wikipedia.  Retrieved on 8/7/20 from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madia_sativa

Never seen them before--just suddenly saw them by the succulents near snail shells and decaying leaves under the shade of the bush.  They curl up easily and will climb walls at night.  Also, a pill bug was found next to them, but no interaction between the anthropoids.  As of July all five of the millipedes have disappeared--not doubt due to heat.  I'll miss them, but the pill bug is still there.  Here is a link from a pest control service that helped me identify my observation:  https://pestkill.org/millipedes/all-types/

description:
Chilean Sea-Fig (Carpobrotus chilensis), photographed near the edge of the blufftops at Wavecrest Open Space in Half Moon Bay, CA.  The relatively small diameter of its flowers (2.0 inches or less) and the rounded-triangular cross-section of its leaves rule out both the "regular" Sea-Fig (Carpobrotus edulis) and hybrids between the two Carpobrotus species.

The small red critters inside the flower are apparently a type of mite.  However, I don't have the foggiest notion which type of mite it might be.  They were crawling over all of the vegetation within about 5 feet of the edge of the blufftops at Wavecrest Open Space.

description:
California Figwort (Scrophularia caliornica), also known as California Bee Plant, photographed at Wavecrest Open Space in Half Moon Bay, CA.  There are four photos in the set of pictures documenting this specimen:

1) Shot 1 shows several a small grouping of California Figwort in situ, including the specimen documented here.  Note its erect habit and height; some of the individuals in this photograph are over 6 feet tall.
2) Shot 2 provides a closeup of the plant's leaves.  Note that the leaves are simple, triangular to lanceolate in overall shape, and heavily dentate on the margin.  
3) As these plants had mostly finished blooming, Shot 3 provides a close-up of their seed capsules in various states of maturity.  The seed capsules show that the original inflorescence was arranged as a panicle, with generally 3 to 10 flowers on each panicle branch. 
4) Shot 4 provides a close-up of two remaining flowers. Note that each of these flowers consist of a highly inflated, reddish corolla tube with an aperture that has a two-lobed upper lip, a single-lobed lower lip, and a single-lobed "wing" to either side.  The upper lip is much larger than the lower lip, with the two wings in between the upper and lower lips in size.  Included inside the corolla tube are two fertile stamens, an infertile staminode, and a pistil (which is often not visible from the aperture).  The two stamens and one staminode can be seen in the apertures of both of the remaining flowers.  The flowers of Scrophularia californica are apparently irresistable to bees, which is why one of this plant's common names is the California Bee Plant.  

References:
1) 'Key to Families,' Jepson's e-Flora.  Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/IJM_fam_key.html on 7/1/18.
2) 'Scrophularia,' Jepson's e-Flora.  Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=11404 on 7/1/18.
3) 'Key to Scrophularia,' Jepson's e-Flora.  Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?key=11404 on 7/1/18.
4) 'Scrophularia californica,' Jepson's e-Flora.  Retreived from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=43849 on 7/1/18.
5)  'Scrophularia californica,' Calflora.  Retrieved from http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-calrecnum=7422 on 7/1/18.
6) 'Scrophularia californica,'  Wikipedia.  Retrieved from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scrophularia_californica on 7/1/18.

description: Nuttall's White-crowned Sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys nuttalli), photographed at Wavecrest Open Space in Half Moon Bay, CA.  As this photograph was taken in late June, all of the White-crowned Sparrows that visit the San Francisco Bay Area in the winter had departed, leaving only the resident subspecies that nests in locations along the immediate coast, such as Wavecrest Open Space.   Known as Nuttall's White-crowned Sparrow (Z. leucophrus nuttalli), this subspecies is characterized by a bright yellow-orange bill, warm brown coloring on the wings, grayish brown coloring on the back with little to no patterning, and a relatively dingy, grayish-white breast.  This individual is showing some signs of feather wear, especially on its back feathers, which is not unusual for this time of the year.
